,"notable_category":["law","education"],"notable_blurb":"Harvard Law School Librarian 1913-1922","primary_url":"https://www.jstor.org/stable/1329010?seq=8","primary_url_label":"Harvard Law Review memorial"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"Harvard Law School Librarian for nine years","body":"After serving as Librarian of the Social Law Library in Boston (1909-1913), he was appointed Librarian of the Harvard Law School on September 1, 1913. He served until his sudden death from stroke on March 24, 1922 — devoting himself to the school 'with complete devotion.'"},{"number":2,"category":"character","header":"1894 horseback wire-fence accident changed his life","body":"Spending his vacation in Colorado Springs in summer 1894, he galloped through the Country Club gate where a careless steward had stretched cattle wire across the entrance. His horse fell with him; he lay unconscious nearly a month and remained an invalid for close upon a year. His sensitive organization 'never regained its old power of rapid and forcible expression.'"},{"number":3,"category":"education","header":"Led his class at Harvard Law in scholarship","body":"In his first year at Harvard Law (1892-93) he led his class in scholarship and was recognized by his fellow students as a man of brilliant ability. He was an editor of the Harvard Law Review, a member of Pow-Wow Club and Phi Delta Phi."}],"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"I00304","children_ids":["HD3350"],"date_year":1896,"end_type":"divorce"},{"marriage_number":2,"spouse_id":"I00305","children_ids":["HD3352","HD3353"],"date_year":1916,"location_city":"Boston","location_state":"Massachusetts","end_year":1922,"end_type":"death"}],"number_of_marriages":2,"cross_connections":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST002"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"military_service":[],"residence":{},"baptism":{},"burial":{"plot